Written to `tools/title-loop/docs/14-dfda596/feedback.md`. Summary of findings:

**LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS** — two compounding bugs:
1. The title spans 4 lines; the algorithm caps joins at 3, so `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` is never formed as a candidate.
2. The best 3-line join (`LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`) is then eliminated by the "shorter wins" dedup rule because `WITH NIGELLA` (a bare fragment) is a substring and wins on length.

**Smażona zielona fasolka** — the bilingual detection guard didn't fire:
- Polish mixed-case titles can't receive the structural heading bonus (+0.10 is all-caps only).
- `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (all-caps translation on line 1) wins that bonus and outscores the true title.
- The bilingual suppression logic requires cosine similarity > 0.4 between the two title forms, but Polish ↔ Korean romanization diverges enough in embedding space that the threshold isn't met.

**Common themes:** all-caps structural bias over-powers mixed-case titles; the 3-line join ceiling; "shorter wins" dedup mis-firing on OCR fragments; and cross-lingual similarity thresholds being too strict.
