{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01V5tcwHTsP4xHyrxorWfVKi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of both failures. Let me analyze them:\n\n**Failure 1: LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS**\n\nInput lines:\n1. `LABANEH`\n2. `BALLS`\n3. `WITH NIGELLA`\n4. `SEEDS`\n...\n13. `MAKES 25 LABANEH`\n14. `BALLS`\n\nExpected: `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`\nGot: `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`\n\nThe title is split across 4 lines: `LABANEH`, `BALLS`, `WITH NIGELLA`, `SEEDS`.\n\n\nLet me trace through what's happening with each line. `LABANEH` is a single word that passes the hard filters since it's all caps and not in the exclusion list, but it fails the structural heading check because it needs at least 2 words. `BALLS` also passes the basic checks, but I need to verify whether it's actually in the non-title words list.\n\nNow looking at `WITH NIGELLA` - this is 2 words, both are 4+ letters, and it's all caps, so it qualifies as a structural heading. `SEEDS` is just a single word so it doesn't. When I check the multi-line join of `LABANEH BALLS`, both words meet the length requirement, so this combination would also be a structural heading.\n\nLet me trace through the actual lines more carefully. After the heading section, I'm seeing ingredient lines like `1 kg / 4 cups Greek yoghurt` and `1 teaspoon salt` that have the characteristic patterns of ingredient entries. I'm checking the vowel-to-letter ratio for \"LABANEH\" — it has 3 vowels out of 7 letters, giving a ratio of about 0.43, which doesn't look garbled. So the burst of short lines starts from index 0, and I'm now walking through the continuation-merge logic to see which lines get combined based on whether the next line starts with special characters. Checking the 3-line candidate `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` — it's 26 characters, not an ingredient, doesn't start with a number, and isn't metadata. For the garbled check, all