ved the threshold and the multi-title guard allowed them both through.\n\nLet me think about what `bestStructural` would be. The embedding scores would need to be considered. The candidates that are structural headings include `LABANEH BALLS`, `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, `BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, `BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`, `WITH NIGELLA`, and `WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`, among others.\n\nIf the algorithm selected `WITH NIGELLA` as `bestStructural`, that would be very wrong. The real title `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` spans 4 lines, but the algorithm only forms 2-line and 3-line joins, so the maximum candidate is `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`. The full 4-line title never enters the candidate pool, which could be the core issue—the joining logic caps out at 3 lines when the actual title needs 4.\n\nThe truncation-penalty logic doesn't help either, since `NIGELLA` appearing in both `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` and `WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` isn't a truncation relationship—it's just a shared word. The check looks for cases where one word is a suffix of another, which doesn't apply here.\n\nSo why did the algorithm pick `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS` over something containing `LABANEH`? Looking at the output, that `+` means both `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` made it into the selected candidates. But `SEEDS` should fail the garbled-text filter—let me trace through: it's 5 letters with 2 vowels (ratio 0.4), it's a single word longer than 3 letters, doesn't start lowercase, and has no mid-text periods. So it actually passes all the filters.\n\nSince `SEEDS` is only one word, it doesn't qualify as a structural heading, but it's still a valid candidate. The real question is why the embedding similarity ranked `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS` higher than `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`. Without seeing the actual embedding scores, I can only guess—maybe `WITH NIGELLA` alone has stronger semantic relevance to recipe contexts, or perhaps the longer option didn't even make the top 25 candidates before selection.\n\nLooking at the prioritization logic, `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` has 4 words (under the 5-word threshold) and is all-caps, so it should rank high enough to survive the cap. That makes me wonder if there's a multi-title guard at the end that's filtering things out. I'm checking the logic that handles multiple all-caps selections to see if it's treating some as sub-headers and removing them. I see that `SEEDS` doesn't have ingredient-like content following it, so it wouldn't qualify as a subheader, meaning both `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` stay as separate titles—which explains the actual output. Now I'm wondering why `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` didn't win as the best structural candidate and get the bonus. It could be that it didn't make the top 25 candidates despite prioritization, or the embedding score favored `WITH NIGELLA` as a more food-related phrase, or the bilingual detection at the pre-threshold stage filtered it out. There might also be something about how position 0 is handled in the algorithm.\n\nChecking the position 0 logic, all candidates at position 0 are in all-caps (`LABANEH`, `LABANEH BALLS`, `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`), so the bilingual detection wouldn't trigger. I'm realizing the real constraint might be the 3-line join limit—`LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` spans 4 lines, so only the 3-line version makes it into the candidate pool, and that's still not explaining why it didn't win structurally.\n\nLooking at the deduplication logic, it filters out longer candidates that contain shorter ones. So if both `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` and `WITH NIGELLA` are selected, the longer one gets removed because it contains the shorter one, leaving just `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` as the final result. I need to trace through the structural heading prefix removal to see if that's supposed to prevent this.\n\nChecking the prefix removal logic now...\n\nThis step removes any selected items that are space-delimited prefixes of the first structural heading. So if the heading is `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, it would filter out `LABANEH BALLS`, `LABANEH`, `WITH`, and similar prefixes—but only when they're complete space-separated words, not partial matches.\n\nThe issue emerges in the dedup phase: `WITH NIGELLA` isn't caught by the prefix filter because the full heading doesn't start with `with nigella ` (it starts with `labaneh balls with nigella`). So `WITH NIGELLA` survives the filter. Then during deduplication, since `WITH NIGELLA` is shorter and contained within `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, the longer one gets removed instead. Combined with the multi-title guard treating both as valid headers, we end up with `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` as the final result—which is the actual bug.\n\nNow looking at the second failure case with the Polish and Korean ingredient names, where the mixed-case Polish title and the all-caps English variant are competing with body text below. Checking the garbled word detection logic...\n\nThe function checks if a word starts with lowercase and has 2 or fewer letters after removing non-alphabetic characters, unless it's in a common short words list. For `zielona`, it starts with lowercase `z` but has 7 letters, so it doesn't trigger the garbled check. And `Smażona zielona fasolka` starts with uppercase `S`, so it wouldn't fail the initial lowercase check either.\n\nNow looking at `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` - it's all caps, not an ingredient, doesn't start with a number, and isn't metadata. For the garbled check, I'm counting the vowels and total letters to calculate the ratio.\n\nMoving to position 2: `그린빈 볶음` is Korean text. When I strip out non-Latin characters, there's nothing left, so it gets flagged as garbled and fails the hard filter.\n\nFor the structural headings, I'm checking if `Smażona zielona fasolka` is all caps by extracting only Latin letters and comparing them to their uppercase versions - but Polish diacritical marks like ż and ą complicate this.  `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` is clearly all caps with three words of sufficient length, so it passes and becomes the first structural heading, earning the bonus.\n\nNow I'm moving into the bilingual title detection logic... Looking at how `selected` is filtered from `scoredForThreshold`, if `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` was suppressed during threshold computation, it shouldn't appear in the final output—yet it did. This suggests either the similarity check didn't trigger the suppression, or there's something else going on with how the scoring works that I'm missing.\n\nNow I'm checking whether `Smażona zielona fasolka` was actually recognized at position 0 and what its cosine similarity to the English title would be.\n\nThe issue is that the embedding similarity between the Polish title and `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (where `BORKEUM` is Korean romanization for stir-fry) likely falls below the 0.4 threshold, even though they're semantically equivalent recipes. The bilingual detection threshold might be too strict when comparing across very different language pairs like Polish and Korean romanization.\n\nThe real problem is twofold: the all-caps structural bonus heavily favors translated headings over native-language titles in mixed case, and the line-joining logic caps out at 3 consecutive lines, missing longer multi-line titles like `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` that span 4 lines.\n\nNow I'm documenting these findings in a feedback file and need to check if the docs directory exists first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11095,"cache_read_input_tokens":21645,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11095},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a7196b8c-4206-4b90-9bdc-acd6511dfbc5","uuid":"203126bf-7ffc-4583-badc-da66085297c0"}
